    <h1 id="title-center">Cory Booker</h1>
    <h1>Candidate</h1>
    <p>Booker has studied at Stanford University and Yale Law School. He has worked as a lawyer and lived in Newark for many years. He played football and was a Yale Scholar. He also spent some time mentoring middle school students. He was elected to the Senate in 2013, where he remains representing New Jersey.
    </p>
<h3>Source </h3>
<a href="https://corybooker.com/meet-cory/">Cory Booker's Website</a>
<h1>Stances</h1>
<p>Booker has three major issues he has expressed on his website. First, Criminal Justice Reform. Second,  Economics. Third, Equal Rights.</p>

<h2>Criminal Justice </h2>
<p>Booker helped draft the First Step Act. This was an act dedicated to reducing recidivism. There was an implementation of systems designed to reduce recidivism. It also redid sentencing guidelines. There was also a prohibition on using restraints on pregnant prisoners, and provisions on storing firearms. Supported Marijuana Justice Act. This is an act to legalize marijuana federally and reduce sentences for those already convicted. It was also partly an attempt to reduce the disparities of those sentenced with different racial backgrounds when charged with drug possession especially marijuana.

<h2>Economics</h2> <p>
Booker has also advocated tax reform. His plan would increase the number of benefits that most people would receive (in effect raising the poverty line higher, and all those that can benefit from income dependent benefits.) A unique idea introduced is that of creat a “baby bond.” This would mean that a set amount of money is given to everyone when they are born, and increases as the child ages. Tax reform is also looked towards as an attempt to reduce disparities between rich and poor, and different racial groups.

<h2>Equal Rights</h2> <p>
Booker has come out in support of LGBTQ+ rights. He sponsored the Equality Act. A bill that would have amended the Civil Rights Act to include sexual orientation and gender identity as protected groups. His website also says he supports Medicare for All, which is usually a single payer program for medical insurance or reduced payment (usually through subsidies) for medical insurance for all or most people. The exact form that this would take under Booker’s plan is still unknown. Finally, Booker advocates for more legal environmental protections due to the impacts on vulnerable communities.</p>
